The paper deals with algorithms for low-rank approximation of matrices, which is a topic that falls under several sub-categories in computer science. The use of sublinear time algorithms suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The paper also deals with information theory, as it discusses the use of oblivious subspace embeddings, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. The use of factorization techniques and the focus on optimization suggest that the paper may also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. The paper also deals with numerical analysis and optimization, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the analysis of algorithms and the use of lower bounds, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category.
